<subSubSection pageId="39" pageNumber="184" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="39.[106,229,574,598]" box="[106,229,574,598]" pageId="39" pageNumber="184">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[106,229,574,598]" pageId="39" pageNumber="184">Comments:</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="39.[106,1097,613,821]" pageId="39" pageNumber="184">
The original description is based on a male and a female (&quot;in einem Pärchen&quot;) from &quot;Lirik im Gebirge von Talysch&quot; (
<bibRefCitation author="EPPELSHEIM, E." box="[391,587,643,667]" pageId="39" pageNumber="184" pagination="11 - 16" refId="ref26548" refString="EPPELSHEIM, E. 1884: Diagnosen neuer Staphyliniden aus dem Caucasus und aus Lenkoran. - Verhandlungen des Naturforschenden Vereines in Brunn 22 (1883): 11 - 16." type="journal article" year="1884">EPPELSHEIM 1884</bibRefCitation>
). Both 
<typeStatus box="[669,758,644,668]" pageId="39" pageNumber="184">syntypes</typeStatus>
are males and deposited in the Eppelsheim collection at the NHMW. The smaller specimen was erroneously sexed as a female by Eppelsheim, obviously because it lacks the male secondary sexual characters on the elytra and the abdomen. The larger 
<typeStatus box="[422,502,736,760]" pageId="39" pageNumber="184">syntype</typeStatus>
with fully developed secondary sexual characters is here designated as the 
<typeStatus box="[300,399,766,790]" pageId="39" pageNumber="184">lectotype</typeStatus>
. The species does not refer to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="THOMSON" authorityYear="1858" box="[737,836,766,790]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Alevonota" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="39" pageNumber="184" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[737,836,766,790]" italics="true" pageId="39" pageNumber="184">Alevonota</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but to 
<taxonomicName authority="PACE, 1983" authorityName="PACE" authorityYear="1983" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Tropimenelytron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="39" pageNumber="184" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[931,1096,766,790]" italics="true" pageId="39" pageNumber="184">Tropimenelytron</emphasis>
PACE, 1983
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="39.[106,1096,835,1043]" pageId="39" pageNumber="184">
From 
<taxonomicName authority="(EPPELSHEIM, 1880)" baseAuthorityName="EPPELSHEIM" baseAuthorityYear="1880" box="[171,551,835,859]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Tropimenelytron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="39" pageNumber="184" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tuberiventris">
<emphasis box="[171,325,835,859]" italics="true" pageId="39" pageNumber="184">T. tuberiventris</emphasis>
(EPPELSHEIM, 1880)
</taxonomicName>
, the only other representative of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="PACE" authorityYear="1983" box="[903,1066,835,859]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Tropimenelytron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="39" pageNumber="184" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[903,1066,835,859]" italics="true" pageId="39" pageNumber="184">Tropimenelytron</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the Western Palaearctic region, the species is distinguished by larger size, longer antennae, a broader head, the much coarser, more defined, and denser puncturation of the forebody, the much less pronounced (i. e. distinctly shorter and less elvated) keels on the male elytra (
<figureCitation box="[1006,1084,927,951]" captionStart="Figs 59-62" captionStartId="28.[189,227,781,803]" captionTargetBox="[195,1169,174,763]" captionTargetId="figure-343@28.[189,1172,174,780]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="Figs 59-62: Alevonota gracilenta (ERICHSON) (59-61) and Tropimenelytron mirabilis (EPPELSHEIM) (62): median lobe of aedeagus in lateral view of male from Turkey (59) and of nanistic male from Italy (60); spermatheca (61); forebody (62). Scale bars: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4793992" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4793992/files/figure.png" pageId="39" pageNumber="184">Fig. 62</figureCitation>
), and by the larger aedeagus. The modifications of the male abdominal tergites III, IV, and VII are similar to those of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="EPPELSHEIM" baseAuthorityYear="1880" box="[346,500,988,1012]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Tropimenelytron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="39" pageNumber="184" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tuberiventris">
<emphasis box="[346,500,988,1012]" italics="true" pageId="39" pageNumber="184">T. tuberiventris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName box="[515,776,988,1012]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Tropimenelytron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="39" pageNumber="184" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mirabilis">
<emphasis box="[515,776,988,1012]" italics="true" pageId="39" pageNumber="184">Tropimenelytron mirabilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is currently known only from 
<collectingCountry box="[106,220,1019,1043]" name="Azerbaijan" pageId="39" pageNumber="184">Azerbaijan</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
